41 IC 36-8-3-20). After June 30, 1993, a law enforcement officer who has
42 satisfactorily completed basic training and has been appointed to a law
ES 80—LS 6159/DI 112

13
1 enforcement department or agency on either a full-time or part-time
2 basis is not eligible for continued employment unless the officer
3 satisfactorily completes the mandatory inservice training requirements
4 established by rules adopted by the board. Inservice training must
5 include de-escalation training. Inservice training must also include:
6 (1) training:
7 (A) in interacting with persons with mental illness, addictive
8 disorders, intellectual disabilities, autism, developmental
9 disabilities, and Alzheimer's disease or related senile
10 dementia; and
11 (B) provided by persons approved by the secretary of family
12 and social services and the board;
13 (2) after December 31, 2024, annual training, which may be
14 completed online or by other means of virtual instruction, that
15 addresses the mental health and wellness of law enforcement
16 officers including:
17 (A) healthy coping skills to preserve the mental health of law
18 enforcement officers and manage the stress and trauma of
19 policing;
20 (B) recognizing:
21 (i) symptoms of posttraumatic stress disorder; and
22 (ii) signs of suicidal behavior; and
23 (C) information on mental health resources available for law
24 enforcement officers; and
25 (3) training concerning:
26 (A) human and sexual trafficking; and
27 (B) high risk missing persons (as defined in IC 5-2-17-1).
28 The board may approve courses offered by other public or private
29 training entities, including postsecondary educational institutions, as
30 necessary in order to ensure the availability of an adequate number of
31 inservice training programs. The board may waive an officer's inservice
32 training requirements if the board determines that the officer's reason
33 for lacking the required amount of inservice training hours is due to
34 either an emergency situation or the unavailability of courses.
35 (h) This subsection applies only to a mandatory inservice training
36 program under subsection (g). Notwithstanding subsection (g), the
37 board may, without adopting rules under IC 4-22-2, modify the course
38 work of a training subject matter, modify the number of hours of
39 training required within a particular subject matter, or add a new
40 subject matter, if the board satisfies the following requirements:
41 (1) The board must conduct at least two (2) public meetings on
42 the proposed modification or addition.
ES 80—LS 6159/DI 112

14
1 (2) After approving the modification or addition at a public
2 meeting, the board must post notice of the modification or
3 addition on the Indiana law enforcement academy's website at
4 least thirty (30) days before the modification or addition takes
5 effect.
6 If the board does not satisfy the requirements of this subsection, the
7 modification or addition is void. This subsection does not authorize the
8 board to eliminate any inservice training subject matter required under
9 subsection (g).
