15 meaning set out in IC 11-10-3-1.
16 SECTION 59. IC 11-10-12-5.7, AS AMENDED BY P.L.6-2021,
17 SECTION 1, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
18 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 5.7. (a) The department shall assist a committed
19 offender who has a mental illness or addictive disorder in securing
20 treatment through an approved Medicaid program, as the authorized
21 representative as described in IC 11-10-3-7 or as a health navigator
22 under the requirements of IC 27-19-2-12, so that the committed
23 offender might be eligible for treatment when the offender is:
24 (1) released on parole;
25 (2) assigned to a community transition program;
26 (3) discharged from the department; or
27 (4) required to receive inpatient psychiatric services while
28 incarcerated to the extent authorized under federal law.
29 (b) The department shall provide the assistance described in
30 subsection (a) in sufficient time to ensure that the committed offender
31 will be able to receive treatment at the time the committed offender is:
32 (1) released on parole;
33 (2) assigned to a community transition program; or
34 (3) discharged from the department.
35 (c) Subject to federal law, an inmate placed in a work release
36 program or other department program involving alternative sentencing
37 programs is eligible for Medicaid covered services.
38 (d) The department may use a community mental health center (as
39 defined in IC 12-7-2-38), IC 12-7-2.1-78), hospital, mental health
40 professional, or other provider certified or licensed by the division of
41 mental health and addiction to provide treatment for a mental illness or
42 addictive disorder through the Medicaid program.
