38 the department with regard to a child, means that:
39 (1) the department has definite and articulable evidence
40 giving rise to a reasonable suspicion that the child or a child
41 residing in the home with the child:
42 (A) has been or is in imminent danger of being physically
ES 80—LS 6159/DI 112

204
1 or sexually abused; or
2 (B) has been or is in imminent danger of being neglected in
3 a manner that would lead a reasonable person to believe
4 the child's physical safety is seriously endangered;
5 (2) there is no less intrusive alternative to the department's
6 action that would reasonably and sufficiently protect the
7 child's imminent health or safety; and
8 (3) one (1) or more of the following applies:
9 (A) The parent, guardian, or custodian of the child:
10 (i) is the alleged perpetrator of the abuse or neglect of
11 the child; or
12 (ii) is allegedly aware of the abuse or neglect of the child
13 and has allegedly not ensured the child's safety.
14 (B) There is reason to believe that:
15 (i) the safety of the child might be jeopardized; or
16 (ii) essential evidence regarding signs or symptoms of
17 abuse or neglect under subdivision (1) on or in the child's
18 body might not be available;
19 if the department's action is delayed or the child's parent,
20 guardian, or custodian is notified before the department's
21 action.
22 (C) The child is a homeless unaccompanied minor and is
23 voluntarily receiving services at an emergency shelter or
24 shelter care facility without the presence or consent of the
25 child's parent, guardian, or custodian.
26 (b) An allegation of educational neglect does not qualify as an
27 exigent circumstance.
