11 SECTION 231. IC 35-36-3-1, AS AMENDED BY P.L.85-2024,
12 SECTION 3, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
13 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 1. (a) If at any time before the final submission of
14 any criminal case to the court or the jury trying the case, the court has
15 reasonable grounds for believing that the defendant lacks the ability to
16 understand the proceedings and assist in the preparation of a defense,
17 the court shall immediately fix a time for a hearing to determine
18 whether the defendant has that ability.
19 (b) This subsection applies to a defendant charged with murder or
20 a Level 1, Level 2, Level 3, Level 4, or Level 5 felony. When a court
21 sets a hearing under subsection (a), the court shall appoint two (2) or
22 three (3) individuals to determine the defendant's competency. Each of
23 the appointed individuals must be a psychiatrist, or a psychologist
24 endorsed by the Indiana state board of examiners in psychology as a
25 health service provider in psychology. An individual appointed under
26 this subsection must be competent and disinterested.
27 (c) This subsection applies to a defendant charged with a
28 misdemeanor or a Level 6 felony. When a court sets a hearing under
29 subsection (a), the court shall appoint one (1) individual who:
30 (1) is a:
31 (A) psychiatrist; or
32 (B) psychologist endorsed by the Indiana state board of
33 examiners in psychology as a health service provider in
34 psychology;
35 (2) is competent and disinterested; and
36 (3) has expertise in determining competency.
37 (d) In addition to the psychiatrist or psychologist appointed under
38 subsection (c), the court may appoint not more than two (2) additional
39 individuals to assist the court in determining competency. Upon request
40 of either party, the court shall appoint at least one (1), but not more
41 than two (2), additional individuals to assist the court in determining
42 competency. An individual appointed under this subsection may be an
ES 80—LS 6159/DI 112

299
1 individual:
2 (1) described in subsection (c); or
3 (2) who is competent and disinterested, has expertise in
4 determining competency, and is:
5 (A) licensed:
6 (i) under IC 25-23 as an advanced practice registered nurse
7 (APRN) with a certification as a psychiatric mental health
8 nurse practitioner;
9 (ii) under IC 25-27.5 as a physician assistant who specializes
10 in psychiatry or mental health; or
11 (iii) under IC 25-22.5 as a physician who specializes in
12 psychiatry or mental health; and
13 (B) certified by the division of mental health and addiction as
14 a competency evaluator.
15 (e) An individual appointed under this section may not be an
16 employee or a contractor of a state institution (as defined in
17 IC 12-7-2-184). IC 12-7-2.1-318). The individuals who are appointed
18 shall examine the defendant and testify at the hearing as to whether the
19 defendant can understand the proceedings and assist in the preparation
20 of the defendant's defense.
21 (f) At the hearing, other evidence relevant to whether the defendant
22 has the ability to understand the proceedings and assist in the
23 preparation of the defendant's defense may be introduced. If the court
24 finds that the defendant has the ability to understand the proceedings
25 and assist in the preparation of the defendant's defense, the trial shall
26 proceed. If the court finds that the defendant lacks this ability, it shall
27 delay or continue the trial and order the defendant committed to the
28 division of mental health and addiction. The division of mental health
29 and addiction shall provide competency restoration services or enter
30 into a contract for the provision of competency restoration services by
31 a third party in the:
32 (1) location where the defendant currently resides; or
33 (2) least restrictive setting appropriate to the needs of the
34 defendant and the safety of the defendant and others.
35 However, if the defendant is serving an unrelated executed sentence in
36 the department of correction at the time the defendant is committed to
37 the division of mental health and addiction under this section, the
38 division of mental health and addiction shall provide competency
39 restoration services or enter into a contract for the provision of
40 competency restoration services by a third party at a department of
41 correction facility agreed upon by the division of mental health and
42 addiction or the third party contractor and the department of correction.
